Solutions of carboxylic acids have properties that they share with other acids.
They react like other acids, for example they react with carbonates to produce
carbon dioxide, a salt and water. When in solution, they ionise and release
Hions, which make the solution acidic (see p.118). But since they only
partially ionise, carboxylic acids are weak acids (see p.122).
